reviewnospace: A trip to this museum is a bit surreal, but then that is the point. Dali designed the building as a theater to exhibit his artworks. There is a large panorama of his works that trace his artistic progress from his early years to the last years of his life. The museum includes sketches, sculptures, paintings, murals, holograms, photographs, magnificent artistic jewelry, and of course surrealistic creations. Also on display are paintings by other artists from his personal collection. The museum is easily visited from Barcelona as a day trip.

The museum includes sketches, sculptures, paintings, murals, holograms, photographs, magnificent artistic jewelry, and of course surrealistic creations. Also on display are paintings by other artists from his personal collection. The museum is easily visited from Barcelona as a day trip.

quote: A Beautiful Museum And Worth Every Moment
reviewnospace:
This is a really fun museum and incredibly interesting. Here's a few important pointers:
1. Buy your ticket and be there first thing in the morning. This is a popular destination, so there may be many "tour bus tourists" arriving, so first thing or end of the day may be your best bet for less crowds.
2. If you put a Euro in the car, Make sure someone is standing at the window of the hearse to let you get your picture. I did this and other tourists made sure to take advantage of the photographs I wanted to take inside the vehicle when my surprise started. The coin slot is at the front of the car.
3. This museum was built around Dali's tribute to his late wife. So the, unless they change his art, it would be hard to design it more accessible to wheelchair.
4. If you drive here, make sure to drive to his home as well. You are definitely missing out if you don't take a drive further North to see his home. It is very interesting too.
5. Make sure to look for all the "secret" ways to look for things. Dali wanted his audience to understand that there is more than one way to look at something.

quote: Well worth the trip from Barcelona
reviewnospace: It is a great demonstration of Dali's unique art and business talent, and showcases his diverse production, with many well-known examples of his style. It is more than just a building full of paintings, as the building itself has been designed/transformed by Dali and the museum to a large extent expresses his ideas. In multiple ways the building is integrated with the art. It was a pleasant surprise to tour the museum, especially when compared to the rather meager Dali exhibition across the Barcelona Cathedral. There are many hours to spend here, I would probably come back if I was near Figueres again.

This is the kind of place that you just have to stroll thru and maybe backtrack once or twice to be sure you see it all. If you have to skip anything skip the jewels but if at all possible see it also. It was so nice we were going to catch a train late that day back to Barcelona so we took our luggage to the Dali Theater and they nicely had a large check room. Also check out the church outside the front entrance to the museum.

Very happy with Explore Catalunya tour!

reviewnospace: The Teatre-Museu Dalí is surely one of the more exceptional and inspirational museums of Europe and well worth a visit even if you´re not a Dalí aficionado. If you are, it´s an absolute treat. The sheer scope of the exhibits is astonishing, ranging from lesser known works to some of his most famous, highlighting the full extent of his artistic genius. It´s one of those places where you could spend days and never get bored, and it certainly is a place to come back to. The buidling is a former theatre that was turned into a piece of art in itself in typical Dalí fashion. The Museum is popular so be prepared for crowds and in particular scholl classes.

A lot of things are incredible, and totally wacky, in a good way. Such a fun museum, a lot of laughs and wonder. I liked how there's a lot of hands-on things to see, which makes the museum interactive.


My only suggestion is bring some small change, because there's a few things that you can (but don't have to) pay for inside, which is just like the icing on top, just adds a little bit more fun to the museum.

Otherwise, loved the museum, and would definitely go back, when we can.

reviewnospace: Lots of others have said it, but I have to repeat. This is an endlessly interesting place. Dali may have been a disturbed genius (or not), but his work is unique, The museum displays are numerous and well done. However, I highly recommend a good tour guide to explain the displays in light of Dali's life and personality. Otherwise, it can just be "a bunch of strange stuff". (A lot of it IS strange stuff, but it's not without meaning and clearly tells a lot about the artist.) I'd also recommend a trip to Dali's home, which is also quite fascinating, although not that easy to get to. It's about 1/2 hour by car over the mountains to the sea shore. Beautiful views along the way.

quote: Fantastic Visit-Highly Recommend a Guided Tour!
reviewnospace: This museum was fantastic and unlike anything I have ever experienced. I highly recommend a guided tour to make sure that you pick up on all the interesting bits that you might miss while being overwhelmed by such an expansive and impressive building. The museum lacks many of Dalí's "most famous" works but the experience this museum gives its visitors far outweighs this negative.

quote: A fantastic treasure house and well worth a visit
reviewnospace:
The Dali Museum has a wonderful and huge collection of works by Dali (and a small amount of his own collection) and reflects the wide range of this important art polymath (and admitted self-publicist). The collection is in the old town museum which became his home, workplace, gallery and shrine. The entry ticket also gives access to the Dali jewellery collection nearby. While booking a time slot is advisable in peak months, it is possible to just turn up and get in. It is, however, always busy, and queuing to see some of the exhibits is inevitable. It is definitely worth it.
Figueres is not the easiest place to get to if you do not have your own transport. A one day package tour (for example from Barcelona) is a convenient option, and usually also covers a visit to the beautiful small city of Girona. Independent travellers can also go by the frequent train service between Barcelona and Figueres. Note that the high speed train (to Paris) goes from Barcelona-Sants to Figueras-Vilafant, which is on the west side of Figueras, but there is a regular bus from the station to the centre. The slightly slower and cheaper regional train from Barcelona-Sants (and Gracia) goes to the nearer, old Figueres Railway Station on the east side of town - an easy walk to/from the centre. Both these trains stop at Girona so a side trip there is possible, if you leave early enough.

Wonderful and moving art about WW11 and the holocaust that was very moving. Dali was an amazing genius of an artist. This museum was well worth the time to see. Loved it.

reviewnospace: You listen and read about this museum, know something about Dali and have seen his work before, but anyway, once you enter the door - you're stunned! It is definitely diferrent from everything I have previously seen in museums. Even his works, because in this setting, they just seem to belong. Everything I thought was mysterious or unclear about Dali's art just clears and comes to its place. The inner garden and the great room in the basement are, naturally, the most beautiful. The artworks there are fascinating, both because of their grandeur, as well as the manner they were created. But, the building itself is also magnificent, with narrow hallways and dark, mysterious rooms. The whole collection is beautifully arranged in this unusual space. To put it shortly - for any art lover, this museum should not be missed! And the important addition - it is CROWDED, so either come early (10 a.m. like we did and waited only 5 minutes in line) or pre-book the tickets. You'll need at least two hours to see everything, so take some water in summer months because it gets warm inside some smaller rooms. I read some comments that it can be claustrophobic but I definitely didn't have that feeling, even though I don't like to be in a crowd. It's just important to plan the visit and prepare to enjoy some of the most impressive art you'll ever see!

reviewnospace: This is a really cool place if you are into Dali. Since Dali oversaw its building and curation, it is kind of like a monument to himself, and it is no less than you would expect. Many many great works, from throughout his career, in many media, well presented and laid out, in a spectacular old building in Figueres. There was a special exhibit on Dali's jewelry which we loved, wish we hadn't done it first but we kind of stumbled into it upon arrival. We enjoyed the easy day trip from S'Agaro where we were staying and we thought this museum was much better and better organized than the Museo Picasso in Barcelona, but both are worth seeing. My 16yo daughter is heading back to her visual arts high school magnet this week with all kinds of inspiration! Dali was such a wonderfully eccentric and fascinating figure, this is an amazing tribute to his talent and artistic ego...

reviewnospace: It is as much an experience as a museum/gallery. Designed by Dali himself, it aims to be a surrealist object rather than a gallery, and provides an extraordinary setting for all the works that are displayed. Dali always surprises you: he appears as mad as a box of frogs but produced some amazing works that both delight and disturb. He is sometimes over the top - as in the gallery of photos of his moustache in different positions - but there are some little treasures, like the jewellery (a brooch of ruby lips and teeth of pearls, literally). It did shock us to see Dali's own tomb in the place - this was possibly not his own choice, since he always wanted to be buried beside his wife, Gala, at their castle in Pubol, out in the countryside. The Theatre-Museum is a very popular attraction, so book in advance, or get there early if you don't want to queue for hours in the sun.

reviewnospace:
Having returned from my holiday I am compelled to leave a review because my wife's review has been removed .
We visited the Dali Museum on 4th August with my daughter , who is a wheelchair user and four other family members . At the entrance we were told that access to the museum for wheelchairs can be made through a side entrance and was shown the way by a member of the museum staff . We were ushered into a narrow overcrowded corridor and then informed that wheelchair access is only possible to a small part of the exhibits and to follow the person to the ticket office to purchase the tickets .
The place was packed ...too many people crammed into narrow corridors , not an environment suitable for a wheelchair user at all. Once at the ticket office we informed the museum manager , who was taking the money for entrance tickets , about it's unsuitability and that we had decided not to see the exhibition . He then refused to let us out until we paid him 70 even though we had only walked 30 meters down the corridor from the side entrance to the ticket office , had been in the place for 3 mins and then took my bag as soon sort of ransom . He was a rude , odious , horrible individual who had no customer skills what so ever . In the ensuing 20 mins he would listen to no reason and continued demanding the 70 , which we eventually paid to get my bag back and gain an exit for my daughter in her wheelchair.
Can not comment on the exhibition as we did not see it .
A horrible, horrible experience in an overly crowded building , managed by a Basil Fawlty manager and made to pay 70 for the pleasure ......AVOID IT LIKE THE PLAGE .

Not a fan of Dali but my wife was keen to see it and, given it was on our way home, seemed silly not to stop by. Very imaginatively displayed and wide variety of art. I liked a lot of his early stuff which seems less self-indulgent and pretentious ( or at least that's how it seems ). Really glad I went. The building in itself is interesting inside and out. One remark was that there was not much by way of explanation,just titles. Think I would have liked to have had an audio guide. It does feel a little like: this man's a genius and great son of Figueres: don't question it !

One final trip: paying car park right next to museum which feels like Dali designed it. Convenient but a tight squeeze !

Whether viewing his oils, statues, holographic presentations, installations (especially the multilevel series of sculptures and paintings - one is left in awe of this artist.

reviewnospace: I took a train from Barcelona Sants, and the trip took only about an hour. Then it was a pleasant 20 minute walk to the museum. The town has excellent signage, making it difficult to get lost. Loved the walk through the town, passing a market, some great shoe shops, a shop that sold ribbons and sewing trims (something I was looking for if I came across it) There was a line up for tickets but it moved quickly. The route through the museum goes up and down levels, and while each room is numbered I think I missed some. The 2nd part of the museum was next door and featured beautiful jewelry pieces Dali designed. I noticed there were lots of cafes in the area, but I was heading right back to Barcelona. This was a great museum, and a must see.

quote: Amazing Art; go early to avoid crowds
reviewnospace:
The museum has an astounding collection of Salvador Dali's art - paintings, sculptures, jewellery and other creations.

Much of it is totally bonkers - fun, silly, sometimes risqué - but always amazing and intriguing. The 'serious' items are really amazing - he was an accomplished painter.

The actual museum is a bit of a rabbit warren - lots of rooms connected by corridors and stairs. It can be quite claustrophobic to be stuck on the stairs while some guided tour marches past.

Great for children of all ages, limited access for wheelchairs or people who need assistance walking.

The actual museum is a bit of a rabbit warren - lots of rooms connected by corridors and stairs. It can be quite claustrophobic to be stuck on the stairs while some guided tour marches past.  Great for children of all ages, limited access for wheelchairs or people who need assistance walking.

reviewnospace: If you are into art this museum is a must. The art itself is magnificent, and the same is to be said about the building. The museum displays the single largest and most diverse collection of works by Salvador Dalí, the core of which was from the artist's personal collection. One of the most spectacular museums I have ever been to. I wish I could be there on a day when there were less people there, but I guess it's not possible.

reviewnospace: After a lovely visit to the Gala Castle at Pubol, hopes were high. Having my small handbag snatched away from me with purse, phone and everything, allegedly because it was a back back, was a bad start. Then entering the crowded museum with no direction and little interpretation made it very hard to get much out of the museum - as other reviewers have said, you can't even assume that the unlabelled works are by Dali and the layout is clumsy. I asked a friend to lend me the money for a (not cheap) guide book but it is not written as a practical visitor guide. When you add the off-hand / rude attitude of most of the staff, the overall impression was of having been ripped off and excluded from the Dali experience by lack of prior knowledge. The management of this museum have a lot to answer for.

quote: A must see! The genius in his own museum
reviewnospace: We are an art loving family, and our son who is 20 already visited the museum, but even his description didn't give it due credit. It is an amazing assemblage of the genius' work, done by him when he was still alive. The theatrical aspect of the museum is not lost on the artist, who was buried in it. I strongly recommend spending the money on a guided tour, as the paintings have so much hidden symbolism that it would take an extensive amount of time to decipher both the meaning and hidden messages in them. As a bonus, you get to skip the lines, and visit the jewelry museum of exquisite creations by the artist

quote: One of the three must-do's for Dali
reviewnospace: It's a dream inside. Literally, at moments you feel you may actually be touching the mind of Dali if you stop and really rest to look into and through his work. His absolute love/infatuation for Gala is unquestioned. Throughout the meseum Dali's brilliance is staring back at you at times satirical, painful, sharp, cutting and visionary. Most people go here not knowing he is buried here. You'll be surprised to see where he is interned - and captivated by those who don't know....idly walking past him and over him as they gaze around.

reviewnospace: Weird and wonderful as expected, but much more in terms of content. Bonus was the jewellery - something I thought fabulous while also crazy, beautiful and fascinating. The theatre has a lot of installation scale work and a good selection of drawings but mostly the layout lets you enjoy the intended dislocated emotions of surrealistic shocks and the crazy, amusing yet disturbing, dream-like works all mixed up. He knew it would shock even repel as well as engage, but this collection also shows meticulous draughtsman-like execution, so you get the sense of all that mad talent you see in his masterpieces of paintings though these are not represented so much here.

reviewnospace: Dali excelled at so many things but marketing himself as the center of the universe was his true talent. The car in the center of the entrance way with the long mast through it and the boat on top with the large tears falling from it. If you put a coin in a box on one side of the car it begins to rain inside and an umbrella opens on top of the mast. I'm not sure I really understand it but it's pretty amazing to see. The room immediately behind it with the picture of Gala that's an optical allusion as it turns into Abraham Lincoln when you look at it from 50 feet back of it. The painting of Dali and Gala on the ceiling looking up at the heavens with you looking up at them seeing them suspended. The allusion with the large lips sofa and fireplace like nose that turns into Mae West from a distance and from above. All of this and much more awaits you at the Dali Museum. Afterwards go into his Jewelers museum and see the very interesting and intricate pieces of jewelry he designed.

quote: No guide books or audio guides are available.
reviewnospace: I am an art teacher. I have studied Dali. I was VERY excited to take my family to this museum. I just assumed that there would be an audio guide provided. Like at all of the other museums we have visited. But no. And the map they give you upon entry is less than helpful. We wandered through the exhibits wondering what we were seeing. Wondering about the back stories. There was nothing. Not until after we went through the entire museum, and were exhausted, hanging out in the gift shop, did I see a guide book for the museum. And by then, it was too late. DONT MAKE THE SAME MISTAKE..... hire a guide or buy the book about the museum for 12 euros. But buy it BEFORE you go through the museum. Good luck....

quote: Wow! Don't Miss Tjis Dali Experience

reviewnospace: Our tour bus drove 2 hours from Barcelona to visit this wonderful museum set up by the great artist Salvator Dali. You will see his paintings, sculptures, drawings,special designs and unthinkable inventions from this superb brain. One week will not be enough if you go and analyze every bit of his art. I followed my tour guide just to get the important information on some of them and finsihed the tour in an hour and a half, but it is not enough if you want to go deep. His love to his wife Gala is respectable and wonderful. Great place to visit and strongly recommended to everybody.

quote: VERY unique museum 2 hours from Barcelona
reviewnospace:
We visited this museum on a group tour. It was a day trip from Barcelona and also included Dali's house in Port Legat and lunch in Cadeques. It takes roughly 2 hours to get to the Museum. The museum itself is amazing and very unique. The visitors become part of the exhibit as many of the aspects of the museum are in 3D, include sculptural elements, and must be experienced, walked through or viewed from certain vantage points to be appreciated.
There is a separate museum of Dali jewelry which is very good and worth it if you have time. There is a gift shop and lots of interesting rooms to explore. I would budget 2-4 hours depending on your interest level in Dali. His art and sculpture is very unique and interesting.

Onward to Portlegit where Salvidore has his home, this too was unusual, 7 fishermen homes made into one. This tour was well worth the effort.

quote: A wow - whether you are a fan or not

Didn't understand much of it but was still fascinated, entertained, amused and often made to feel a bit spooked.Superbly laid out too in this beautiful building. A must see.

quote: An immersive visit to one of the most imaginative artists ever known

No it is not the British Museum, but yes it is so, so much more than a one room gallery.

reviewnospace:
If you enjoy bad service, cramped hallways of poorly hung art and fighting your way to look at Dali's artistry from an inch away, then this is the museum for you!
The only interest the museum has, is making money, they do not care if they go over capacity, which seems to be all the time.
The art is hung in hallways so tiny that you can barely stop to actually see some real beauty without being knocked or pushed.
Tourists are constantly trying to take photos, even though it is prohibited and the staff on floor do not seem to care.
Poorly managed, overcrowded, expensive and frustrating.
The collection is absolutely stunningly impressive - the only positive point.
NOT WORTH THE VISIT.

quote: Excellent overview of Dali: a "bucket list" must see
reviewnospace:
The museum presents an excellent overview of some of the variety that Dali engaged in- and he tried his hand in much more than "just" painting!

Prior to visiting we watched an excellent BBC programme (Salvador Dalí: A Master of the Modern Era) on youtube which helped prepare us for the breadth of understanding of his art and life. The museum then presented the eccentricity, and also what I might call the more serious side, of his tremendous contribution to art. Don't get distracted by the kitsch, there is also amazing depth and on display. Thus, I am starting to appreciate how amazing he was, and will need to explore more of his works in Madrid and New York.

Figueres is easily connected to Barcelona via the Renfe train, and a great stop for a night or a week. Worth the trip from Barcelona. This is a "bucket list" must.

We booked first available tickets (online) for the morning and avoided long queues (even in April!).

Knowing he helped design the museum makes it even more precious. There were several pieces I didn't like, but that's the beauty of art-if one piece speaks to you, it's a success. More than one piece spoke to me. If you're anything of a Dali fan, GO! No excuses. And slow down, enjoy. My husband and I were amazed at the different things we saw from different vantage points in the museum.

We bought our tickets online and had zero wait to get inside. I highly recommend doing this.

quote: A wonderful day trip from Barcelona
reviewnospace:
This certainly ranks among the most unique museums one will encounter and left us with a new-found appreciation of Dali's work. There is a lot more to the experience than visiting the museum website can do justice to. Being able to see the wide range of his work made it clear that he wasn't just a surrealist but could create in any style that he chose.
The train trip was easy to negotiate and the walk to the museum wasn't difficult. We combined a late morning visit to the museum with an overnight stay in Girona on the way back to Barcelona. It made for an excellent little trip and we were very happy that we took the extra time to see the amazing Dali museum. Highly recommended (at least off-season).

The round trip train fare was about $45.00 USD and is about an hour + depending on whether you take the local train or express (TGV). Its a short walk from the train station to the center of town (maybe 1/2 mile). We took a taxi in and he definitely took us the long route, only to discover how close of a walk it was ( for the walk back to the Figueres station!) Not really much to do in Figueres aside from the Dali Museum but that alone well worth the day trip. The museum is pretty incredible. So much of Dali's work all in one location.

reviewnospace: Our son lives in Barcelona so we try to get here once a year and we havent had the chance to visit the Dali museum before this. l It is a commitment: a 1 hour train ride costing $32 round trip each, a bus ride into the city for another euro per person each way, we unfortunately arrived with 3 groups of very exuberant french students, but the otherwise empty museum (I would hate to be here in the summer) was a unique pleasure. Dali apparently designed it himself and it is unique. The amazing range of his imagination and skill is breathtaking. Even tho I have seen a wonderful Dali retrospective in Atlanta, it did not hint at his amazing range. Over all, it was well worth the trip and the expense. I highly recommend you keep this in your itinary if you are traveling to Barcelona.

quote: A Must-See Dali Masterpiece! A Fantastical, Wacky, Bonkers, Arty Extravaganza!
reviewnospace:
FANTASTIC! Some of Dali's most wacky, bonkers & wonderful creations displayed in a converted theatre for an all-round auditorium-like viewing experience!
Of course, Dali himself was behind the design & layout of this place, so it really is the perfect space for a museum/gallery! It's not one of those stuffy old museums... here, you're allowed to take as many photos as you like of all the amazing paintings, fabulous sculpture & interesting artefacts, and staff on the doors & around the building are all very friendly, lending a generous spirit & open atmosphere to this fantastical Dali paradise!
Personal favourites include the central courtyard (open to the elements) where the old theatre stalls once sat. And of course the old stage area with that gorgeous, massive Dali painting overseeing all the modern day visitors to this glorious cacophony of surrealism! Definitely not to be missed! xxx

quote: Not many of his best works
reviewnospace: My husband and I took the trip to the Dali Theater Museum from barcelona and were a bit disappointed with this visit since there were not many of his better known artworks on display and there was little information about his life and his art. I can understand that his best art is displayed in other museums, but I wish they had more information about him and his art. At least a chronological presentation would have helped, to allow us to see his development as an artist. I think Dali preferred his work shown in no particular order, but I wish there was more information given. The long travel from barcelona was not worth it.

quote: A Must See(And Experience) in Spain
reviewnospace: The Dali Theatre-Museum in Figueres was for me the highlight of our recent trip to Spain,and we had many great experiences during our 10 day trip around the country.I never fully appreciated the brilliance,psychological insight,and satiric humor of Dali until our afternoon long tour of this marvel,including the remarkable Museum of (Dali) Jewelry next door.The upraised boat with the blue plastic tear drops hanging from the boat's underside in the courtyard area reflecting his sadness over the death of his beloved wife Gala was very moving,and the room using various objects to comprise the image of Mae West was clever beyond imagination.Dali designed the museum and the placement of items himself,and his wit in doing so is on display throughout The museum is a short walk from the Figueres Train Station,a one hour ride on Renfe from Barcelona.Plan on having a great time here.

The building is the highlight but after the initial very striking courtyard it disintegrated into a messy shambles with almost no written context to aid visitors. It left the unfortunate impression that Dali could not paint very well. None of his "great" Surrealist paintings were there. There was no information about his life. The jewels were hideous unless you are a fan of tacky bling. Go to any museum with a proper jewellery collection and you will see incredible craft and beauty - but not here.

quote: Do not go there if you are a lover of Dali
reviewnospace:
Yes, do not go, especially if you are a true lover of Dali, because:
- you will see only a few of his famous works - museum does not possess a good collection despite its name
- you will not be provided with a single piece of information on the works which are on the display
- even those works which belong to Dali and you could possibly admire are displayed in very narrow corridors there you cannot observe them
- museum is filled with works of other artists on which there is no information - who these artists are and why they are on the display
- museum staff is the most careless that we encountered during all our visit to Barcelona

Instead, if you are a truly lover of Dali:
- look for a good exhibition which purposely collected his works and head there - be it somewhere in a big cities of the world which are easily reachable nowadays.

TA is a great place to help others as long as we are sincere.

Every picture hides a different story and its up to you to discover it on your unique way. Its not only interesting visit for the ones who appreciate art but also for the ones who doesnt have much in touch with. I felt the energy of the place and it really took my breathe, so I would recommend anyone to spend some time in this magical house of true art.

reviewnospace:
To simply call Salvador Dali a surrealist would be like saying Thomas Edison made good peanut butter sandwiches.
Dali drew, painted, and sculpted in every style, including his own. He was also a master showman. He marketed himself brilliantly. When you enter the museum, which he designed, you enter a whole other world. It's the world of Dali. His talent was boundless, as is the organization of the museum, which seems to be a hodgepodge of his works. Don't be fooled. Everything is a setup for the next, or perhaps a coda for the previous work. Even his custom-made Cadillac has a catch to it. It rains inside. Se it. Enjoy it.

quote: Worth a side trip to Figueres
reviewnospace: I have never been a huge fan of Dalí and the surrealists; however, this museum is a thrill. It was completely designed by Dalí himself and is indeed a single integrated piece of art all by itself. The exterior is wonderful and entertaining, as is the sculpture around the front. Once you are in, the introduction explains that while a pathway is arranged from 1-22, Dalí himself would have rebelled at any kind strict sequence, so we did it all wickely-wackely and had a great time going against the flow of the visitors. Close to the end we realized we had missed one whole floor which provided us with a completely unexpected "dessert". It was also where we found most of the Bosch-like drawings and the melting clocks. Try to visit the museum when you are not pressed by schedule and take your time. Every minute you spend there is rewarded by new treats.

reviewnospace: Visited the Dali Theatre Museum on a rainy day in October. It is amazing and a "must do" if you are anywhere near in this area of Northern Spain. reviewnospace:
Figueres is a dainty little town, with a traditional Spanish personality, and a twist of madness. And yes you guessed it, this madness has been influenced by the crazy coconut Salvador Dali.

Dali is my favourite artist. He brings alive sexual desire with a theatrical flair. His creativity with the anatomy and physiology of the human body leaves you feeling amazed at its beauty, but yet questioning its possibility.

He had an uncanny ability to allow the taboo of sexual desire, masturbation and fornication - to be natural, normal and without shame or judgement. As it should be.

Dali's creativity stems far from the canvas, to sculptures, jewellery, theatre, movies and the list goes on.

I spent over 5 hours in the Dali Theatre- Museum, and this has been one of the highlights of my trip so far. It is worth the train ride from Barcelona to embrace the works of this genius.

Enjoy

quote: Enlightening : now I know who Dali was!
reviewnospace: The old theatre was where Dali wanted his showcase to be. Like him, it is a grand , dramatic representation of beauty specifically seen in his art, his jewelled pieces of sculpture, his film clips etc. He designed a room where he mimicked the ceiling of the Sistine chapel. It was incredible, very surrealist. His Works darken as the period of WW2 approached. I especially loved the series called Aliya. Watercolour drawings of concentration camp scenes, the ship :the Exodus and others about israel's creation. Of course there were lots of dripping clocks.A slow time consuming drive but well worth it.

reviewnospace:

Since I never understood Dali till this trip, I preferred to book a guided tour since it was a family tour with 2 young kids.
We biked via hola shalom company and they took us in a great tour via Girona to Figueres.

Worth the air fare alone!

quote: Imagine seeing Dali when you are the only person in the room!
reviewnospace:
I was traveling with my 25 year old grandson. When he was 13 we were in London together and stumbled on an exhibit of small Dali pen and ink drawings. There began his connection to Dali. So it was special that when we decided to meet in Spain, we were able to visit the museum in Figueres.

Almost everyone who commented on the Teatro-Museo complained about the crowds. So many people traveling today, especially in August, and they all want to visit the same 10 sites. How to avoid that?

I read that there were night hours at the Museum. I was able to book tickets for the museum and an English language tour for a day that fit our schedule. Night hours are from 10:30 PM to 1 AM, (pretty amazing hours for a NYer!). At the start of the evening it was crowded, but the museum staff kept saying how fortunate we were to be there when it was relatively empty!

The tour was really wonderful and informative. We learned so much about the museum and Dali's involvement in every detail of its construction. It lasted from 10:30 to midnight. Then we were invited to the courtyard for a glass of champagne.

After midnight the crowds began to dissipate. By 12:30 there were so few people that we were able to enter galleries alone. What a special gift to be alone with our thoughts in front of Dali's works of art.

If it fits it in your plans, do go at night. Tours are offered in several languages and are a nice addition. But definitely buy your tickets in advance.

The museum tickets also includes entrance to an adjoining site, Dali's Jewels. Interesting, but if time is limited, skip it and stay in the main building.

quote: Weird, fascinating. Worth visiting. Even our kids loved it.
reviewnospace:
Compared to a typical art gallery, this was very engaging and interesting throughout. A wide range of sketches, paintings, installations, jewellery, and general weirdness. We overheard a few comments from one of the guides which revealed a depth to some of the large paintings which were not immediately obvious.
Note that this is not just a building full of paintings on the walls; the art is much more integrated into the whole building and is much more of an exploration than just walking about in some dry rooms which can be the experience in some galleries.
Our kids 10,13,15 all enjoyed it and thought it was great fun, which is not their normal view of art museums. We queued only for about 10mins as we arrived at about 950am or so and were near the front of the queue. The queue seemed badly organised as those who booked in advance just queued with everyone else. Mad.
A highly enjoyed destination; also enjoyed Figuerues more generally - had a nice atmosphere and may return to just wander around some more.

quote: Wow is all I have to say.....this is simply one for the bucket list, a must see!
reviewnospace:
Unique, unusual, eccentric, different, brilliant, these are words you think of when you visit the museum. The Dalí Theatre-Museum is simply incredible. As the largest surrealistic object in the world, it is located in the former Municipal Theatre, a former 19th century construction that went bankrupt, destroyed at the end of the Spanish Civil War. On its ruins, Dalí decided to create his museum with careful attention to selecting everything he loved. So from the outside in, he created all the interesting details of the museum, from the funky looking gold egg shaped ornaments on the rooftop, all the other ornaments on both the outside and in. Inside are many of his famous paintings, artwork, and fun and immagination. Dali of course is buried in this museum - which is his own shrine to himself. You have to love his imagination and creativity.
We visited the spectacular Salvador Dali museum  gallery that only Dali could design. Of course it is chocker-block full of his unusual  uniqueeccentric art, vending machines to put coins in to see different displays of his art. The uniqueness of his art and this museum goes on and on. The museum is located in the town of Figueres where Dali was born. We each got one of the t shirts from the gift shop....who could resist his unique design. Would recommend to anyone. Would go back again. It is the main draw to this town. We traveled from Besalu to Figures, then onto Pals and Peratallada, en route to Tossa de Mar. This is a very special museum!

quote: Out of this world - a ten star attraction!
reviewnospace:
This is one of the best museums/art galleries I have ever visited. Very competitively priced at 11 per person (including the separate jewellery exhibition).

Externally, the building itself is fantastic. Internally, a fantastic display of Dali originals and complete public access to all the exhibits. No flash photography but still plenty of camera action possible without flash. An amazing range of artwork, sculptures, drawing, objects on display. All very well laid out. An easy to follow, logical guide leaflet available free and in many languages. I would recommend that you use this to work your way round the museum.

I would advise an early arrival (we were there by 9.00am), as by the time we left at lunchtime the entrance queues to get into the museum were very long (and outside in the direct sun!). I would also recommend purchasing entry to the jewel exhibition, which is housed in a separate building less than 100m away.

If in Figueres, please do not miss this its a must see!

reviewnospace: I'm glad I went. The art is intriguing. The experience, however, was terrible. 1) Dahi needed an editor. There is too much stuff, packed into limited space, and he refused to provide context. I wish we had hired a guide. All my learning came from overhearing guides. And that was always fascinating info I'd never have figured out on my own. 2) there are too many visitors. It's mobbed, adding to the challenge of spending time exploring and pondering how to figure out the puzzles of his work. 3) the cameras are a nightmare. In our group of 12, everyone commented on how disruptive it was to have to share viewing with people who took space just to get photos. They don't look at the art, they just snap pix which is surprisingly disruptive and takes from the experience of thinking through the images.

quote: Top Attraction That Attracts A Crowd
reviewnospace:
The museum is stuffed full of Dali's works (and other artists from time to time). There is plenty to see and some of the works are quite breathtaking.

This is a TOP attraction in the area, though. Lots of people come to visit and the queue to get into the museum in the middle of July on a mid-week day around lunch-time did take 30 minutes to get to the point of paying for tickets. And there were a lot of people inside the museum.

The wait and the bustle of people are worth the effort though.

NOTE: The works are a "history" of Dali's work. Some of his more famous pieces will be found elsewhere (like the museum in Florida, which I've also visited though many years ago). That said, for those interested in art, it is a "must-see"!

Stunning fantasy open courtyard as you go in, and it just gets better. We were delighted to go in early and see the famous Mae West settee..huge red lips, while it was quiet. Go can take a camera in, only rule no flash photos. We were pleased to have seen Dali and Galas home at Port Ligat first, this is the stunning showpiece. Loved the extraordinary huge ceiling painting of Gala and Dali ascending to heaven..dominated by the huge feet of Gala! Dalis tomb is here, sadly not in Pubol with Gala as he wished. An extraordinary place.

On entering the museum I had to take a good 10 min wait to get ready once seeing the amount of work on display. I found it all extremely interesting, interactive and mind boggling at the same time. Mad man or genius is the normal question, I can only say his technique was flawless and his choice of subject sometimes ridiculous, but it all works and I loved it! Even our none Dali friends enjoyed the experience, so give it a view!

quote: A place to visit if you like Dali
reviewnospace: I was visiting North Catalunya and Figueres is a nice town to visit. It has this Dali Museum with many of his pieces and a building designed for him. I am not so much fan of Dali but if you are you will love it.
titleopinion: A place to visit if you like Dali. I was visiting North Catalunya and Figueres is a nice town to visit. It has this Dali Museum with many of his pieces and a building designed for him. I am not so much fan of Dali but if you are you will love it.

reviewnospace: This place is a must for those who are into Dali or who want to see one wild and crazy art museum. Dali was certainly a talented fellow, but some of his stuff borders on landfill art: let's go to the dump, see what we can dig up and stick it together and voila, call it ART!! But to be serious, I am sure that there is some meaning in the art he created, but good luck trying to decipher it all. What I found impressive about this place was the range of his creative expression. The guy just had no bounds in media or imagination. Remember to visit the jewelry exhibit at the end which is worth the price of admission alone. This place is pretty big so plan on spending at least 2 hours. I leave you with this thought: if Dali had Gorilla Glue and access to Ebay, the results would've been stratospheric.

quote: A Treat for the Eye and the Imagination
reviewnospace: Enter Dali's world of creativity and imagery -- you will not be disappointed. Indeed, you'll have fun as you explore both his principal museum and his Jewelry Museum, the latter of which will take your breath away. The Viatour day trip to Girona and Figueres gets you to the Dali Museums in Figueres. Overall, it's the most enjoyable, informative and economical way to partake of all that Girona and Figueres have to offer the visitor.

reviewnospace: This museum has one sole aim : to make as much money as possible. The museum is small but they cram in as many people as possible. At times there are as many as three or four guided tours taking place in one small room, each guide competing to speak louder than the others. Very difficult to hear the explanations or see any of the paintings. A money-making conveyer belt which makes for a stressful and disappointing experience. There are so many great art museums in the region... avoid this one!

reviewnospace: Salvador Dali was a master craftsman and creative genius. Like any artist, the more you know about the person, the more you can appreciate and enjoy their work. This particularly holds true for Dali. You may or may not enjoy his work, but unless you've studied, you probably won't understand it. More than most, this is an artist that requires some explanation so if you come to the museum that he designed himself, you'll get a lot more out of the visit if you go on a guided tour.

quote: Amazing artist with so much versatility & fantastic sense of humor.
reviewnospace: Dali is by far my favorite artist after visiting Teatro-Museo Dali. Its overwhelming and breathtaking. Give yourself several hours to absorb and enjoy this cute little town, Figueres, Spain.

The museum is wonderful! Take your time and look at the art, find out all the clever details about the pictures. There is no café or nothing in the museum, so plan your visit. A lot of stairs and toilets only in one place at the groundfloor of the museum (very neat and tidy and many toilets available though) so with children there was a whole lot of running up and down the stairs.

quote: Nice but not easy to get around

quote: a window into a complex mind
reviewnospace:
Dali made full use of his wealth to remodel and refurbish a burned out theatre with his quirky art, along with some of his personal art collection. To most of the world familiar only with his melting clocks and stick -like drawings , this exhibition will be eye-opening.
Expect crowds- even in the off season there are busloads of students there on field trips. An early start is recommended.

quote: Creepily beautiful and interesting for everyone

The guides over there know extremely much about Dali's life and the meaning of his paintings. You might not even like his style but the stories are interesting, therefore I definitely would recommend you to visit this museum with a guide. The museum has been created by Dali himself when he was still alive (which explains the look of the building) which makes it even more interesting. Finally, we also learned that Dali did not just painted but for example, he also created jewelry.

In short: please just visit this amazingly interesting place. But do not expect to see his most famous works such as the clocks and elephants because those are in New York and somewhere else.

reviewnospace:
The museum is as unique as Dali himself was! The architecture is surprising, featuring huge eggs on the roof! The artwork is nicely displayed, the exhibition rooms are large, making for a pleasant experience even on a busy day. Loved the painting of Gala/Lincoln. Very creative. Not to mention the furniture that, seen through a large magnifying glass, turns into a woman's face. My favorite piece was a gorgeous oil painting Dali did during the Spanish Civil War, of a dark beach with a lonely telephone no one seems to call or answer.
The museum shop offers a wonderful mix of gifts inspired by the collection, and a great selection of books. Whether you are a Dali aficionado or not, make sure to visit the museum. You won't be disappointed!

reviewnospace:
I took my family to the Dali Museum on a day trip from Barcelona. The only way to sum up the experience of going to this museum is chaos reigns everywhere. The museum was mobbed and people were everywhere. The layout of the museum is strange as you need to keep walking in circles - much like the Guggenheim in New York - only the corridors are much smaller and you are cramped in many locations.
So why the five stars? Because Dali is a genius and his work is amazing. Even without his famous painting The Persistence of Time - which is in the Museum of Modern Art in New York - his other works are brilliant. You don't even have to like art to love this place. There are plenty of visuals everywhere. Just one word of warning. If you don't want your young children see endless amounts of naked women in both paintings and models, bring a blindfold. They're everywhere!

reviewnospace:
The Dali Museum in St. Petersburg Florida inspired us to become admirers of Dalis work, so we were excited to visit the Dali Theatre-Museum in Figueres and Dali House in Cadaques last month on a Viator tour from Barcelona with lovely guide Julia.

We spent a couple of fascinating hours at the indoor-outdoor museum which is designed to spotlight a wide range of Dali works and relics. A visit to the exhibit of the exquisite Dali jewels is included. It was a sleepy Sunday morning in November; the museum was not overly crowded and it was possible to take our time and linger where we wanted.

Dalis craftsmanship is so superb and the range of materials he mastered was amazingly broad. This is the perfect place for showcasing the imagination, artistry and wit that made up his spectacular genius.

reviewnospace: Visiting The Dali Museum in Figueres, Catalonia is an adventure in itself. A feast for the eyes and imagination. We took the bullet train from Barcelona. the museum is a short walk from the train station. The museum in an ancient ruin of a theatre that has been retro fitted with stunning galleries. This museum is not very handicapped friendly, due to the origins of the building and the shoulder to shoulder crowds. However it is well worth the visit. I must say I was not much of a Dali fan before visiting, but the trip really did change my opinion of this famous artist. We had the benefit of having an excellent tour guide for this trip who gave us great narrative as we progressed though the museum. If you have the time while visiting Barcelona, this side trip is well worth your visit. I do regret that our tour did not allow us time to roam the town and shop. I could have easily spent the day.

quote: Was he a genius or mad?
reviewnospace: Salvador was born and lived in Figueres, about a 1 hour drive north of Barcelona. He converted the town's theatre into a fantastic museum. Here you can see his development as an artist, the fantastic creativity he brought to his work and the multiple dimensions and techniques he explored. Make an appointment ahead of time and plan to spend at least a half day to explore this important art museum

reviewnospace:
I had only a day to explore the world of Dali so chose the most accessible museum by train, in FIgueras, which is easily reached by regional or fast train from Barcelona. If you are a Dali fan or have a passing interest, I would recommend a visit. While I was visiting off season, I did so on a Saturday so there was an early tour bus group. Once the tour bus left, it was an easy museum to visit. There is a lot to absorb here. In addition to his more known works, e.g., the car with the boat hanging over it, there were some wonderful other works that truly exhibited how skilled an artist Dali indeed was. The guy was unique, that is for sure. Had I had the time, I would have gladly visited the other two museums in the area. I did not reserve ahead but one can do so and it is advisable during more popular times. The Dali jewels were also on display nearby when I visited and they were wonderful to see. There is not much to see in this town but I grabbed a quick and unimpressive lunch before I headed back to the city. There is a nice farmers' market in the center of town on the way to the regional train station on Saturdays, should that be your day of a visit.

I recommend this place highly.

reviewnospace:
This is like an entertainment park for adults. Dali is a very playful person. You can tell from the exterior of the building, it is composed of eggs and bread. Very very funny. Dali said using eggs and bread to decorate the building because everyone can relate and recognize them. ^^

Don't miss the little jewelry gallery. It housed one of the world's best Dali designed jewelry piece. (i think) Totally took my breath away when i saw it!!!

Dali has many games to play when the people inside the building. The thinker sculpture is being very seriously thinking.....and there is an octopus getting ready to attack him from the ceiling. And on the ceiling, you do not see the lovely angels' faces, instead you saw angels' feet and sole, getting ready to be fly to heaven. very very funny!!

You will be amazed of the amount of works Dali did in his lifetime. He also worked on furniture pieces, video and pixel arts, installations, jewelry.....etc. He also collaborated with one of my favourite photographer, Philippe Halsman, on a book just focus on Mustache. very very funny!!

Get ready to get entertain!! Highly recommended!!

quote: Get a guide...or else be art ardent art lover.
reviewnospace:
One thing about museums is that they are best understood along with a guide. Else, you just might struggle for get your bearing right. Especially so if the museum happens to be of the eccentric artist called Dali...

It was a good thing we had a guide. A very patient woman, who actually waited so many times for the group to assemble and reassemble. Dali was a genius, that I already knew. But watching the works of the master for the first time left me awe struck. I don't understand art much, but I do like to appreciate a good thing when I see one. And the museum was full of such good things.

Two works that struck me were Dali's concept of no thing having one single perspective and the the piece on May West, that also happens to be an apartment.
.
.
And just to spook you. Dali's grave is in the center of the exhibition hall. It was the wish of the great man that people walk all over his tomb. And walk all over they do..thousands in one single day.
.
Nothing much to do in the town except for this museum.

quote: Worth the day's driveA MUST for Dali fans

I had a Dali day.
From here to his birthplace in Port lligat it was a fulfilling day.

This welcoming environment starts the ride and what a ride it is.providing a timeline was absolutely fantastic and now assists one when pondering dali's vast array of work.
He was prolific.
He was fun.
He was mad.

Upstairs is narrow and makes it difficult to stop and look sometimes

Not to be missed is his jewellery housed in a separate buildingwhimsical, magical and with his etchings seeing his vision come to fruition is outstanding.

Most convenient way is take the full day tour...

reviewnospace:
The most amazing museum ....make sure that you take euro coins with you as many of the exhibits are motorised and you need to put in a coin to see them working. Your ticket will also entitle you to visit the jewellery exhibition which should not be missed. It is truly awesome.
Many of Dali's famous works of art and paintings are on permanent display, allow plenty of time to wander round and appreciate all the nooks and crannies. Remember Dali himself established this museum in the old theatre and he laid it out in his own quirky way. After your visit there are many gift shops, cafés and bars nearby. Get there as close to opening as possible in the height of the season to avoid queues. It is especially busy on rainy days. Visit their website and you can buy timed tickets in advance. In August they have special visits at night including Cava!

reviewnospace:
The museum has an unforgettable look from the outside with the bread loaves on the walls to the giant eggs on the parapets. The entrance is not where you think it would be and you need to go around almost the back to get in. The museum covers almost all facets of Dali's art, but it is crammed into such small spaces it is hard to appreciate the works of art. The museum is packed and corridors are narrow and the constant flow of people makes it difficult to study the art as one would in a larger more spacious place. Photography is allowed without flash which is nice. Also note there are sections of the museum that some people will miss because the path is not well defined. The curving galleries are nothing more that narrow corridors and art is placed all along these corridors making it hard to view. The jewelry gallery is separate from the main museum and not so crowded. It is worth the extra price to visit this gallery.
The museum has a very nice gift shop with lots of fun items to buy. There is also reproductions of jewelry in the jewels section that are very nice.
If you like Dali, this is one of the certified authentic museums and should be a treat to see. If you are staying in Barcelona be aware the train ride up and back can take hours and make this an all day outing.

reviewnospace:
Where to start... opening times and online ticket booking times didn't correspond on their website; once clarified we arrived at the museum to find staff rude and unhelpful.

After paying I had to check my small handbag in to their left-luggage room designed for heavy walkers rucksacks and push chairs only then to subsequently find that other visitors with a similar style bag had been allowed to enter the "museum" without issue and also found a push chair in one of the galleries (so a disparity of permission granted).

At the end of the tour, which to be honest contained only one or two recognisable Dali works, and an awful lot of other artists works, I enquired (of the left-luggage room attendant) where the famous, melting clocks and stilt-walking elephants were... to which I was informed the majority are exhibited in museums and galleries around the world... ergo this museum displays the "leftovers" which quite frankly were not that interesting for a family of five who had driven four hours to look at them. Their website is disingenuous.

reviewnospace:
We were on an Azamara cruise and took a cab from our port in Palamos to Figueres to see this museum in Dali's home town. It is really fun . There is a very large collection of Dali paintings, sculptures, jewelry and holograms. It is fascinating to see both the evolution of Dali's art from very traditional painting to very unconventional works and the incredible scope of artworks that Dali created. The sculpture in the entry hallway of a female figure poised on top of a vintage Cadillac is very striking. There are many significant and entertaining works and it is the largest collection of Dali's art assembled anywhere in the world.
I highly recommend spending several hours enjoying this museum.

In my view it mainly contains secondary pieces and unfortunately contains very few pieces / references to his melting/wilting clocks which I think are some of his best works.


Despite this was had a very good visit, nice lunch at a local restaurant and it was well worth the 100km trip to get there

reviewnospace:
I must admit that we ended visiting the Dali museum only because we had a spare day and had done enough of beach hopping! :) Although we appreciate good art in any form, we hardly knew anything about modern art let alone surrealist, cubist, and what not! But boy, this museum took our breath away as much for the extraordinary variety of Dali's work as for the beautiful structure of the museum and the ambience/impression it manages to create! One well and truly feels in presence of the genius of Dali, and his imagination almost turned us dumbstruck! An absolutely unmissable experience on Costra Brava, perhaps not suitable for kids of any age.

Top tip: Get there as early as you can - we were straight on to the ticket window at 10:30 and there was mile-long queue at noon! This place can get *very* busy and you lose the tranquility a little bit. Also DON'T miss the jewellery museum just round the corner, just as jaw-droppingly beautiful a display of amazingly intricate pieces! Btw, there's a car park for the museum which is not very obvious from the street in front if you went there using a satnav. We managed to park on the street nonetheless.

reviewnospace: We first visited the Dali Treatre-Museum in Figueres in 1992 and every time we're back to Barcelona we make the time to revisit. Every time is as if it is the first! Not so much because of the actual paintings exhibited - most of his renowned works are outside this museum - but because of the feeling you get of who the artist really was! Definitely a genius - not sure if he was as crazy as he wanted us to believe. I am every time moved by the Christ's Head (no colours, just shades of gray): innocent yet mature, suffering yet enduring - it makes me cry... The expression of the Madonna on his Pieta is also a moving experience. Dali painted fabulously in all sorts of technotropies - he was an artist in every sense of the word and that you realize only after a visit to this specific Museum. This year we were also lucky to see his Jewelry Collection - what a sight! A MUST if you are around this year.

reviewnospace:
We have been to the Costa Brava twice in the past four years and made it a point to visit the three main Dali attractions while we were there (his home in Cadaques, Gala's home and this museum). This museum was by far the most expansive collection of work and provided the most insight into his vast artistic range and body of work.

For our visit to this museum we left it too late to book tickets and, with two young children (5 and 8), we didn't think we would be able to wait in line for the several hours that all of the reviews said it may take to get into the museum. Fortunately my wife found the private tour offered by guiding.es for a few Euros more per person. The experience we had was worth far more than the few extra Euros we spent per person. Our guide was incredibly friendly, knowledgable and fluent in English. The tour group was private consisting of the six members of our family and the guide, far better than other guided tours that seem to have up to 30 people with headsets to hear the tour guide. Our guide was able to get us into the museum without waiting in line and took us to specific pieces of art and areas of the museum and gave us insight into the importance of the pieces in his life's collection of work.

Importantly for us the guide was also able to keep our boys interested and involved throughout the experience in spite of their young age. Both of them told us they really enjoyed the experience and learned from the tour guide. I highly recommend this museum and the guided tour provided by guiding.es to make the experience even better.

quote: Dali at night is just amazing!

Lot of people taking pictures and that takes a lot of time because the hallways are not so big. But the atmosphere at night is just breathtaking! In the garden they were serving glasses of cava to the guests, and a black and white movie of Dali was projecting on the wall. Really nice atmosphere with everyone just relaxing and drinking.

So if you wanna experience a museum visit differently I recommend the night visit! Also Figueres is beautiful at night to walk :)

Even my boyfriend liked it and yes he doesn't like museums at all ;)

Also you can book easily your tickets on internet, it will save time at the line!

quote: Makes you think, but a must see just to appreciate
reviewnospace: The setting is an old theater, and the museum planners use the space efficiently. Dali's work is amazing, from portraits that look like photographs to stereography to jewelry to sculpture. All the famous melted clocks are here, and the various phases of his work are clearly illustrated with large numbers of his work. In order to understand all the symbology (which is everywhere in his art), I recommend a good book beforehand to explain why he uses drawers in figures, the origin and meaning of the clocks, and others. Visitors will not be disappointed - this is an amazing museum holding the works of a true genius, though at times I admit I was puzzled by his work. It is two exhibits - the theater with his art, and a separate exhibit hall for his jewelry. If you are anywhere within range of Figueres, Dali's birthplace, it is worth the time to visit.

Hundreds of first rate pieces, each with multiple ideas pouring out of them. Just go. I can't say enough or anything adequately. Go when it opens to be intimate with the work. Worth a trip of hundreds of miles to get there. Stay overnight in Figueres (Hotel Duran was excellent). You will not regret it.

quote: Definitely Worth the Trip to See This Museum
reviewnospace:
The Dali Theatre-Museum is simply outstanding. This was Dali's home at one time. The art displayed is magnificent in terms of quality and quantity. We spent three hours or so in the museum, and never tired. And then as we thought we were departing the museum, we see that there is an exhibit of jewelry designed and made by Salvatore Dali. I never knew he made jewelry, and what we saw exhibited there was beautiful in concept, design and workmanship. Two full stories of Dali jewelry, breathtaking.

When we did depart, we then spent considerable time viewing the theatre with its ornate spires. Again, engaging and wonderful to look at.

We were driving from near Carcassonne, France to Barcelona, and thought we would make a brief stop at this museum. Each of the four of us was mesmerized by the art, the jewelry, and the architecture. We stayed much longer than expected, and had a wonderful visit. I highly recommend visiting this museum.

quote: The extraordinary legacy of the moustachioed gent aired to perfection.
reviewnospace:
The pretty capital of Alt Emporda is famous for the fact that it bred two extraordinary characters in a short period of time. One was the eccentric Dali,the other, the famous maritime legend of Figueres, which figures why the town is honours his feats. Perhaps its the evocative atmosphere of the Avenue where his monument is located,lined with plane trees and lovely 19th century houses,for its the place as well,for the evening stroll.

But its the Dali brand that has made this town pop,with the Dali museum,the most frequented after the Prada in Madrid,a personal legacy of the moustachioed gent,fielding works from all periods of his life. Dali's hand guided by his exuberant imagination,can be sensed everywhere. His quirky pieces bring joy and puzzlement ,once you realise the torment and turpitude his experiences in life led him to create with such depth and whimsy.

In fact,in order to sum up the enormous breadth of his creativity,you have to slow your amble to pause and savour each painting and sculpture. I particularly was taken with the grotesque ceiling painting in the hall of the Palace of the Wind.

Once outside,there are in the town some Dali-free zones. The church of St. Pere,a toy museum and the lovely Museu de l'Emporda. A few km to the south of town,Pubel showcases Dali's medieval castle.

reviewnospace: We visited this museum during our week-long vacation in Barcelona. It's an excellent day trip - especially combined with our stop in Girona on the way back to Barcelona. I wouldn't say that we're huge Dali fans, but this museum has some of his most interesting works and it was very well presented. The Mae West room is probably worth the price of admission, but there's so much more. The only downside to our visit is that they let way too many people in - it's basically wall-to-wall people. It would have been better if we they had reserved visiting times with less of a crowd. However, the art was worth seeing and it's a very pleasant train ride from Barcelona.

reviewnospace:
I first visited this exhibition many years ago, the visit on Tuesday 22 April 2014 was with my wife, she had not been there before.
Our holiday was based in Santa Sussana about 90 minutes away by train. The information desk at the railway station in Figueras is excellent, they supplied a detailed map and directed us to the museum.
I could not possibly recommend anyone to go there after our experience.
The queue was about 20 metres, but it took over an hour to gain entry. The queue is neither managed nor stewarded, I saw many family groups head straight for the front and push in, the woman at the single entry desk was not interested in any protests at this behaviour. The museum obviously has a policy of accepting far too many dis-organised school trips as there were countless groups of mostly French school children ushered into an adjoining group entrance.
This utterly destroyed any hope of appreciating the exhibition. They ran amok, spending the whole time photographing themselves and each other and the exhibits. Squealing, shouting and running around is fine in a theme park, but not at a museum. Their teachers, probably glad to be free for a few hours were conspicuous by their absence. The few museum stewards I saw, sat listlessly in the corners of the exhibition rooms endlessly shouting No Flash and being totally ignored. It was like a zoo, with the chimps on the loose. Salvador Dali is the epitome of surrealism, and a master of optical illusion. It was simply impossible to appreciate any of this.
I apologised to my wife that this visit had been utterly ruined. It is clearly a policy of the museum to over whelm the exhibition with too many groups presumably to maximise their income to the detriment to others.
Visitors would be far better advised to use the entrance money on a beer and a snack and then browse the many Dali themed souvenir shops.

quote: Art as humour - who would have guessed?
reviewnospace: Dali had an amazing imagination and a great sense of humour. This was the first time we had been in a museum that made us smile, sometimes laugh and always wonder at the incredible imagination that could conjure these outrageous creations. It was also very cool to be in a museum created by the artist. The very building and the rooms were all part of the exhibit. Things aren't explained. It isn't about "understanding" Dali. It is about sharing his sense of humour. Our young adult kids loved it and so did we.

reviewnospace:
We came with very high expectations and ended very disappointed.
The building and the overall visual effect of the main halls is overwhelming.
However the museum is a total shame.
You get a one page brochure with very little information.
There is no option for an audio-guide.
Most of the works are not even named.
Some are named but don't have any further information about them.
Without a guide you are just wandering around and getting pushed by the crowds.
The museum is overcrowded and there is no control on the amount of visitors.
The place could be a gem with a just little attention, but it is not!!

reviewnospace:
A lot of people around the world have assembled Dali works, but I think this is the most representative (except for a temporary exhibit I saw in Rome a couple of years ago, which did a great job of recounting Dali's life and artistic legacy).

Aside from what I expected, this museum (which is not so easy to get to, being in a relatively small city 2 hours from Barcelona) offers a truly splendid, knock-your-socks-off collection of jewelry designed by Dali. Not your usual Tiffany pins and necklaces, each piece was a tour-de-force combining common crystals with precious and semi-precious stones, in whimsical, totally-original settings, such as a spindly elephant, and a set of wings that physically flap. It's worth coming just for the jewels.

In the main museum is a good collection of paintings and a few "real-object sculptures" by Dali. I especially appreciated the Homenage a Lincoln, which starts as a female nude as you see it up close, then dissolves into a recognizable image of Lincoln's head as you move farther away.

We were disappointed. Try to join a guided tour or do your homework on the museum before going.

quote: Not only is it a Museum for Dali's artwork but the museum is art!
reviewnospace:
This place was a theater where Dali had his first exhibit, and the city wanted to put some of his art in a museum, so Dali decided he would rework the whole place and turn it into art!

The buildings is a piece of art and all of the arrangements inside are amazing. All of his creations here make you think and see outside of your comfort zone. It is eye opening and helps you become appreciative of unique and different.

This place is worth your time for a visit.

reviewnospace:
This is an amazing museum created to Dali's specification, so you know you're in for a treat.

He might have been a shameless self-promoter, but he was also an astonishing genius and this museum gives a greater insight into his phenomenal skill as an artist and his ability to surprise and intrigue with his work.

I got a terrible fright when I belatedly went to the museum's website and it said that it was sold out - but it turned out that was just for guided tours... So we didn't have a guide, which may have been interesting, but certainly is not essential.

I recommend also heading to his house for a tour, it's not too far (37km, but the road is very windy) and it felt like it completed the picture of the amazing man.

reviewnospace:
Whether or not you are a Dali fan, or not even an art appreciator you should visit this intriguing place. We were astonished at Dali's wide variety of art styles. Best known for his melting clock faces, we were amazed to see that he was also a fantastic conventional artist. We also thoroughly enjoyed his whackier pictures and creations which are well represented in this ex-theatre which he turned into a museum. We spent over 3 hours there and it seemed like just minutes, and would have spent longer if we had not been on a coach trip.
It is great that you take photos of everything (without flash) so we have hundreds of photos to enable us to enjoy the artwork again at home at our leisure.
Arrive as early as you can to avoid the crowds.
It's a unique experience - do try it.

We visited on a Thursday morning and the only negative I have to say is that the museum was so crowded with tour groups it was difficult for us as a couple to get around them and get an up close view of some of the pieces. I don't know if there would be a day with less tour groups but if there is, visit then!

There you'll find bags and chairs on the ceiling, raining car, entrance in the form of a mouth and, of course, the famous "interior face". Some pieces of Dali's art start moving with a euro or 20-cent coin, so it is really like a theatre.
A must-visit place for everyone who is interested in art.

quote: Loved the place but too many tourists!
reviewnospace: The museum is stunning and a tribute to Dali throughout his life. Well set out across many rooms, although sometimes a little difficult to climb the staircases and meander through the tight corridors. Worth the effort to see this amazing work on display. The downside is its popularity and the fact there are so many tourists visiting. My advice would be to go very early or do an evening tour with the eerie lighting. Miss the crowds as much as possible, or otherwise you will not get the space to appreciate all the beautiful work.

reviewnospace: I recenty spent 7 fantastic days in Barcelona. Anyone who has been there will attest to the endless cultural activities, architectural and historical sites and outstanding restaurants that Barca has to offer. That being said, I could not have been more disappointed with the Salvador Dali Theater Museum, which is noted as the 2nd most visited museum in all of Spain! (How this could be true, is completely baffling to me.) Thankfully, another reviewer had warned our group of the long lines and we made the effort to get to the museum when it opened. An hour later, the narrow halls of this maze of a building were crowded to the point of critical mass. Had we arrived at 11, the wait to get in would have easily been 2 hours, maybe more. My disappointment stems from the complete lack of seriousness, scholarship or historical relevance paid to the legacy of this master in this institution. There are no educational materials provided to the visitor whatsoever. There is no rhyme or reason to the installation and the collection, while it does have a handful of interesting early works, most of it resembles a circus fun house. It is in my opinion that the basic tenants of Surrealism, as was stated on the one map of the building, allows for this intended confusion is completely false. I was so sorry I wasted the better part of a day visiting this place. In addition, the town of Figures is nothing to go out of one's way for. With so much incredible art and architecture in Barcelona, I would warn anyone interested in culture to spend your time doing other things there rather then spending anytime visiting the Dali Theater Museum in Figures.
titleopinion: Disappointed by Dali. I recenty spent 7 fantastic days in Barcelona. Anyone who has been there will attest to the endless cultural activities, architectural and historical sites and outstanding restaurants that Barca has to offer. That being said, I could not have been more disappointed with the Salvador Dali Theater Museum, which is noted as the 2nd most visited museum in all of Spain! (How this could be true, is completely baffling to me.) Thankfully, another reviewer had warned our group of the long lines and we made the effort to get to the museum when it opened. An hour later, the narrow halls of this maze of a building were crowded to the point of critical mass. Had we arrived at 11, the wait to get in would have easily been 2 hours, maybe more. My disappointment stems from the complete lack of seriousness, scholarship or historical relevance paid to the legacy of this master in this institution. There are no educational materials provided to the visitor whatsoever. There is no rhyme or reason to the installation and the collection, while it does have a handful of interesting early works, most of it resembles a circus fun house. It is in my opinion that the basic tenants of Surrealism, as was stated on the one map of the building, allows for this intended confusion is completely false. I was so sorry I wasted the better part of a day visiting this place. In addition, the town of Figures is nothing to go out of one's way for. With so much incredible art and architecture in Barcelona, I would warn anyone interested in culture to spend your time doing other things there rather then spending anytime visiting the Dali Theater Museum in Figures.

I was in and out in probably less than an hour. I took refuge in a local tapas place and enjoyed the tapas, quite tasty.
All I can say if you are not a Dali fan, you may not find this museum to your liking. I definitely was disappointed in the experience.
