quote: Loved the Jewels exhibition, hated the museum
reviewnospace:
I'm only giving this 2 stars because of the Jewels exhibition - something you could easily miss but is absolutely superb and very unusual.

The theatre-museum itself was a huge disappointment. I'm really interested in Dali and have been to exhibitions dedicated to him in Paris, London and Singapore. I had high expectations coming to his hometown and resting place and the glowing reviews only added to that. What I hated about the place:
- tiny corridors crammed with people
- not a single line of commentary, explanation or insight on any of the works, rooms or installations. No guides or audio guides. Nothing about Dali himself
- no thought given to display or arrangement of the works. Most of them you can't see all that well due to lighting and positioning.
- very few "iconic" works - it's mostly sketches and small-ish drawings which, although interesting, are not as "finished" or "accomplished". The fact that there are entire grim corridors of them lined up takes away their individuality too.
- odd exhibtions by other artists at random places. Here too no explanation is given (you actually need to search pretty carefully to even find the name of the artist) and you don't really know what you've stumbled upon
- dumb layout means you wander to the end of a (tiny, cramped) corridor and have to turn back amidst the crowd

I could go on, but you get the idea. It's also not very well connected to Barcelona and tickets sell out online over a week before the date in summer. There is only one cashier at the ticket office so queues are long (and not shaded). Regarding trains: we took the high-speed from Barcelona Sants to Figueres Alifant and then had to pay 10 EUR of taxi to get to the museum.

It's an expensive, frustrating day out and not worth the trouble.

quote: monty python meets disney meets pink floyd

reviewnospace: I normally would rate this museum very highly because of Dali's importance to Catalunya and surrealism, BUT it was so overcrowded during our last visit that the experience was seriously diminished. Our most recent visit was in August, and we had to stand in a ticket line outside with nearby smokers for over an hour since online sales were suspended. Once inside there were long lines for many exhibits. There appears to be no limit on how many visitors the museum will admit at one time, and the extent of the crowding created a lot of jostling, taxed the air conditioning and even made for thoughts about crowd safety in the event of a fire or other problem. If you avoid the crowds, you will likely have a great experience, so plan around the midday body-packing of summer, especially if you want to take a serious and unhurried look at the excellent collection there.

reviewnospace:
This is our second visit to Figueres to see Dali`s museum. On leaving the public car park the first thing one notices is the large blue glass geodisc cupola (over sized golf ball !!) surmounting the roof; this illuminates an internal court which was the stage of the original theatre. Walking around the building towards the entrance and looking up, one cannot help but smile at the oversized egg decorations and statues at parapet level--is this a sign of things to come? Then one arrives at the front façade erected in 1849; the theatre was destroyed by fire in 1939 and remained as charred walls until work began in 1970 and the museum officially opened in September 1974.
There are 22 rooms over four floors exhibiting paintings, drawings, sculptures, displayed settings and the tomb of Salvador Dali. The internal courtyard is open to the sky with displays and statues around the ivy covered walls.
One travels between the exquisite the bizarre and amusement, all of which can excite pleasure and puzzlement. If you are not a follower of Dali it is still worth a visit. We enjoy it.

quote: Not worth a detour, an expensive tourist trap
reviewnospace:
It is supposedly one of the most visited museums in the world. Be prepared to stand in line for more than an hour, to finally find yourself in a small museum flooded with people.

Although the exterior of the building is promising, the museum is not worth waiting in line and the entrance fee of 12  (2013). You will not find any of the famous paintings of Dali such as "The Persistence of Memory", "Metamorphosis of Narcissus", "Sacrament of the last Supper", "Christ of Saint John of the Cross" or any painting with elephants, melting clocks, ... .
It is a collection of Dali's "second class" work: drawings, unknown paintings, early work, furniture, some fun objects.

In addition, there is no apparent organization of the exhibited work (period, year, theme, ...) and no signs explaining each object ( title of the work, year of production, ... ).

To make everything worse, the museum is filled with people ( you need to stand in line IN the museum to see artwork closer! ). No way to look to work from a distance, share ideas with your companions, ... , a rather stressful visit.

quote: Top marks! - even better with the guide
reviewnospace: As we had a look at the queue trailing down the street across the plaza and on out of site we noticed that the tourist information office just outside the museum offered guided tours at set times in a range of languages. So for E20 instead of E17 we got a great insight into the work of a hugely talented artist. We wouldn't have got anything like as much information by just wandering around ourselves. Following the museum tour the guide took us for a short tour around the centre of Figueres adding a lot of background to Salvador Dalí's life - it was well worth it. In addition, the ticket we got from the tourist information gave us entry to the the Dalí jewellery museum. This is a must if you're in Figueres.

reviewnospace: Dali- I had always thought of him as eccentric and colourful, but until our Australian family visited this museum, I had not realized what a versatile and supremely talented craftsman he was. Often inspired by his wife, Gala, Dali created masterpieces in furniture, jewellery,mosaic, charcoal, paint, ink, photography and pretty well anything else that triggered his imagination. The museum is colourful and easy to navigate, if you follow the recommended paths. Each space is unique and quirky. Our three children, aged 12-15 were awe-struck by the magnitude and off-beat nature of Dali's works. It was definitely worth the day trip - even all the way from Carcassonne! A memory of a lifetime and one of the most memorable museums I have ever visited .PS Leave your backpack or large camera bag behind!

reviewnospace: What a great find in a completely obscure part of Spain. Despite having to endure a long wait [due to queuing] to get inside, the Museum is completely awe inspiring. I would not call myself artistically inclined but this is a totally interesting museum based on one man's life work and we are glad we discovered in the small town of Figueres, [150 mins north of Barcelona via AP7). The collection of art works here show someone who was either troubled, completely high most of the time or a true genius way ahead of his time. The devotion to the human form [especially female] is compelling as are the large works in the various corners or displays inside the Teatro. Make sure you also take in the jewelry collection, in a separate building.

reviewnospace:
This was amazing, even with all the crowds. I'm not a great fan of Dali, not that I knew a lot about him, and was really only going because my husband wanted to, and it was raining, but the experience was just overwhelming. To see so much of his art in one place allowed me to appreciate how innovative and creative he was, and so ahead of his contemporaries. It was also possible to see just how good he was as an artist, in terms of his drawing and painting skills. But really, it is Dali's imagination and breadth of vision that was the most striking. I can't say that I really understood all that he was trying to convey, but it was liberating to get some insight into his mind and preoccupations.

Be aware, that parking can be difficult and expensive. We parked in the car park located right next to the museum and even early in the day, it was hard to find a park. Also, the spaces were very small, so if you have a large car (we only had a polo), you may find it hard to park.

As well, there was quite a long queue to get in, and we were there before the main tourist crowds, so investigate if you can pre-book. Our tickets gave us entry into another Dali exhibition of his jewellery, which was fabulous.
titleopinion: Excellent experience. This was amazing, even with all the crowds. I'm not a great fan of Dali, not that I knew a lot about him, and was really only going because my husband wanted to, and it was raining, but the experience was just overwhelming. To see so much of his art in one place allowed me to appreciate how innovative and creative he was, and so ahead of his contemporaries. It was also possible to see just how good he was as an artist, in terms of his drawing and painting skills. But really, it is Dali's imagination and breadth of vision that was the most striking. I can't say that I really understood all that he was trying to convey, but it was liberating to get some insight into his mind and preoccupations.  Be aware, that parking can be difficult and expensive. We parked in the car park located right next to the museum and even early in the day, it was hard to find a park. Also, the spaces were very small, so if you have a large car (we only had a polo), you may find it hard to park.  As well, there was quite a long queue to get in, and we were there before the main tourist crowds, so investigate if you can pre-book. Our tickets gave us entry into another Dali exhibition of his jewellery, which was fabulous.

Once you are back at the train station , don't go back to Barcelona yet : You must make a 2-3 hours stop at the small town of Girona (Jerrona) , and only then - take the train to Barcelona .

quote: Love Figueres...LOVE Dali... LOOVE the museum
reviewnospace: Surreal.. you know it! One of the most amazing kookiest creative brains of the 20th century, the Dali museum doesn't disappoint! The exhibit is fun, well curated and diverse. I didn't even realize that Dali designed jewelry! It was awesome and so unique. Only piece of advice is to really take your time with certain pieces of art. He was a great fan of illusions and master of altering your optical view if you allow it. I noticed many tourists skim past many of his art work that you had to stop and look twice. Like the 3D effects on his Gala double art where you press your nose to the glass to create the effect. There's also his duality art pieces like the Lincoln portrait/naked woman on balcony... or his pieces where there's a metal vase on top... people fail to look into the vase to see the actual vision he had in store.. so when you go, take a breathe, go slow and enjoy the ride or you'll be upset you missed out.

quote: A visual treat at every corner
reviewnospace: We visited the museum from Barcelona. The train ride was easy enough, and there are many trains from Barcelona to Figueres and vice versa. Visiting this museum is like being a kid in a candy store - it is visual spectacle and without the shadow of a doubt, the most interesting museum I have visited. Dali surprises you in ways that you cannot imagine. You see the work of a great artist, and what makes the museum so special is that Dali himself was the creator of the museum. You are not just visiting the museum to admire the pieces on display - the museum itself is Dali's work of art. Make time to visit the museum, you will not regret it.

quote: Largest surrealistic object in the world. Don't miss it when you are in the neighbourhood.
reviewnospace:
The theatre-museum has a wide panorama of works of Dali and it is really amazing and impressive. You can see his progress, starting from his artistic experiences (impressionism, futurism, cubism etc.) to the works of the last years of his life. His surrealistic creations are really impressive.
If you are in the neighbourhood, make time to visit this museum but...........you may find a long queue waiting at the entrance. Either go early in the morning, just after opening hours (09.00 to 20.00 hours from 1 st July to 30th September. And From 1st October to 30th June 10.30 to 18.00 hours) or about later in the afternoon. You need approx. 1 hour to see everything.

(I eventually found an English speaking passenger) Whew!!!. The trip was good and the Dali Meuseum spectacular. Well worth the long wait to get in. They even let you take photos which is unheard of in any gallery I've been to. This guy was surely on drugs. Amazing building as well.

The entrance fee is 12E Reasonable. Figures is surprisingly good. Much nicer than I expected.

reviewnospace: Having travelled a round trip of 4 hrs to see Dali's work we found a long queue for tickets. That aside once inside the volume of visitors entering in one go, eliminates any possibility of enjoying or contemplating the work of Dali. A frenzy of cameras and phones clicking around us, people running in all directions in the absence of a clearly marked viewing route. The noise and shouting. Result: a great artists work demoted to a fun fair attraction. Compared to other museums, this one needs to have a serious rethink.

A real surrealist masterpiece. I'd recommend staying for the evening and exploring this cute little village.

reviewnospace: If you dont like Dali you will find this theatre/ museum weird and probably think its utter madness. If you appreciate Dali's art from when he started as a young boy and carried on through his lifetime doing more and more surreal art and paintings you will get a very good interpretation of his art throughout his life! Its a long way from Barcelona but you can go via a couple of trains and not very expensive. You are greeted by a stack of televisions with broken screens outside the museum/theatre stuffed with dolls and that is for starters. You work your way around the museum which is very well sign posted and it has to be as there is SO MUCH to see you could miss! You go and up and up the staircase and visit all the floors and from the top you can see the bottom floor which looks like an open air patio. The walls are draped with his most magnificent art work modern and classical and in the centre is the masterpiece...a gansters car from the 1950's with lifesize dolls in the car holding brollies as its raining on the car and there is no roof to the car. This is real water cascading down on the car. Its a long way from Barcelona but you can go via a couple of trains and not very expensive. You are greeted by a stack of televisions with broken screens outside the museum/theatre stuffed with dolls and that is for starters. You work your way around the museum which is very well sign posted and it has to be as there is SO MUCH to see you could miss! You go and up and up the staircase and visit all the floors and from the top you can see the bottom floor which looks like an open air patio. quote: Weird, wild, but ultimately not worth it

Others may feel differently, such is the subjectivity of art.

reviewnospace: This is one of the most extraordinary experiences anyone can have in an art museum. The range of Dali's work that is exhibited is impressive. His work is so detailed and this collection is so large, that if you really want to enjoy this museum you should take a guided tour so that you do not miss out on any little, yet interesting details and you should be willing to spend around four hours or more to wander around by yourself. Many people wait in line for hours, but the best advice I can give for visitors is to buy the guided tour. It is about twenty euros per person and they not only give you a guided tour of the museum, but a tour of the town where Dali grew up! This was the best part! They take you to see where he grew up and if you go you will learn the secret of the grasshopper and get to see it yourself.....

reviewnospace:
My wife and I and two friends decided to drive down from France where we were staying for New Year (about 40 min drive). None of us are artists, nor are we particularly keen on art; however we all thoroughly enjoyed this experience (as well as a nice lunch in the sunshine in December at a restaurant near the "Ramblas" about 5 min walk away).
The experience starts as you queue outside (less than 10 minutes) when you notice bizarre art on and around the building. You go inside and then into an outdoor courtyard to be met by a full size car, raining on the inside. Once you have worked out the number system of the various galleries (1 - 22 I think) you can then follow the pathways round, stairs up and down etc This really adds to the experience as each room is done differently. There is so much art that although we took about 2 hours, we felt we could easily have spent a lot longer. There is also the usual shop at the end if you want to buy some Dali on a t-shirt, mug, poster etc. Overall, if I was an artist or really into art, I would absolutely love this place. I am not, yet I still thought it was absolutely fantastic and a highlight of our holiday.

I just returned from a European acation and I want to tell you about the Dali Museum in Figueres.

We parked at the train station in Figueres and walked to the attraction in only 20 minutes. Just follow the signs or ask a local for directions.

We took our time and spent about 4 hours taking in all of the sights there re to see. I recommend reading a little about the museum before you go to familiarize t\yourself with what to expect to see, such as the Mae West room at the top of the building which some people missed because they did not know about it or its location. It is also nice to know that you can put small coins into things like the Cadillac car and make it rain! Dali was quite an entertainer and his personality shows right through here at his museum and also his final esting place which you will see! Have fun, that it what the man wanted....

reviewnospace: Went to the Dali museum in Figueres when travelling in Costa Brava. It definitely is something not to be missed when in the region, esp if you're a fan of Dali. The building itself is amazing from the outside - the eggs and bread rolls gives an indication of the whacky-ness and quirkiness inside. We went there early in the morning, so didn't have to wait too long for tickets but there was already a sizeable crowd. There is a floor plan which gives a brief description of the significant art work (not just Dali's but those of other artists) housed in the building, though it does say that visitors don't have to follow the rooms round by the numbers. I was struck by how versatile Dali's work was and it really was a weird and wonderful world in the museum. It definitely gave a sense of the bizarre world of Dali and the amazing imagination in his work. I didn't find the entrance fee steep considering the amount of work to appreciate and mull over, also having been to Barcelona, we were used to having to pay even more for Gaudi's buildings. We spent about 2 hours there including a visit to the Jewels section. Figueres itself is a pretty town and worth spending some time in. Definitely recommended!!

reviewnospace:
If you visit Spain and like Dali, this museaum is where he and his wife Gala lived, so a must see!

Dalí was a skilled draftsman, best known for the striking and bizarre images in his surrealist work. His painterly skills are often attributed to the influence of Renaissance masters.[1][2] His best-known work, The Persistence of Memory, was completed in 1931. Dalí's expansive artistic repertoire included film, sculpture, and photography, in collaboration with a range of artists in a variety of media.

Dalí attributed his "love of everything that is gilded and excessive, my passion for luxury and my love of oriental clothes"[3] to a self-styled "Arab lineage", claiming that his ancestors were descended from the Moors.

Dalí was highly imaginative, and also enjoyed indulging in unusual and grandiose behavior. His eccentric manner and attention-grabbing public actions sometimes drew more attention than his artwork, to the dismay of those who held his work in high esteem, and to the irritation of his critics.[4]

I consider this museum worthwhile visiting even for those who are not fans of surrealism in general or of Dali in particular. It's quite different from any other museum I have visited.
I found both the building itself and its design as well as the items on display astonishing and inspiring. For Dali-fans, this is heaven.
One note: The museum doesn't give you a lot of background information on the person of Dali or his life, it's really more about his art only. However, Figueres forms part of the Emporda triangle (together with Cadaques and Pubol) in which more Dali-related sights can be found.
True, the musuem is pretty crowded. Due to the lack of a special sequence of visiting, it may be hard to figure out in the end whether you really covered everything, leading to you passing several halls twice or even more times. Still, a great experience, don't skip it.
Figueres itself is a small, cozy provincial town and worth a stroll. The train connection to Figueres coming from Barcelona and Girona is fine.

quote: Fantastic representation of the man and his work
reviewnospace:
Well worth the trip we made from Barcelona to Figueres to see this exhibition. Even if you have little interest in Art or prior knowledge of Dali's work, this exhibition gives an amazing insight to the workings of the human mind. His skill, vision, imagination and eccentricity give truth to his self proclaimed genius. Take time to look closely as many of the exhibits reveal much more than a cursory glance might indicate. Don't expect to see many of his better known works as these are exhibited in museums across the world but the museum he designed and planned for his home town of Figueres is an outstanding legacy. Also don't miss the second museum just round the corner (entry is included with your ticket) as the jewels reflect another aspect of his work and are masterpieces of exuberance and extravagance.
There are a number of options for getting to Figueres from Barcelona. We opted for the train from Passeig de Gracia station which was relatively straight forward and gave us more freedom and control than an organised tour would have done - it also cost less than half the price of the tours we saw advertised in Barcelona which included a visit to Girona. However as the train goes through Girona this is something you could easliy do after Figueres if you wish. We preferred to soak up the sunshine in a little restaurant at the square in Figueres and enjoy Tapas and Cava - sheer bliss
titleopinion: Fantastic representation of the man and his work. Well worth the trip we made from Barcelona to Figueres to see this exhibition. Even if you have little interest in Art or prior knowledge of Dali's work, this exhibition gives an amazing insight to the workings of the human mind. His skill, vision, imagination and eccentricity give truth to his self proclaimed genius. Take time to look closely as many of the exhibits reveal much more than a cursory glance might indicate. Don't expect to see many of his better known works as these are exhibited in museums across the world but the museum he designed and planned for his home town of Figueres is an outstanding legacy. Also don't miss the second museum just round the corner (entry is included with your ticket) as the jewels reflect another aspect of his work and are masterpieces of exuberance and extravagance. There are a number of options for getting to Figueres from Barcelona. We opted for the train from Passeig de Gracia station which was relatively straight forward and gave us more freedom and control than an organised tour would have done - it also cost less than half the price of the tours we saw advertised in Barcelona which included a visit to Girona. However as the train goes through Girona this is something you could easliy do after Figueres if you wish. We preferred to soak up the sunshine in a little restaurant at the square in Figueres and enjoy Tapas and Cava - sheer bliss

to there, even if you are not into art, as I'm sure you would realise
how many different talents he had,and yes, we actually enjoyed it.

quote: Dali's genius and quirkiness all on display
reviewnospace:
A worthwhile hour trek up from Girona to visit this museum. Examples of many of his works are on display, and the price of admission to this surrealistic and quirky museum includes admission to the adjacent Dali-Jewels museum which showed an aspect of Dali I was not aware of. And make sure you you spend the time to wait in line to see the Mae West Room. I won't say more, but you've got to see it!
As much of a fan of Dali as I am, I reluctantly give the experience a 4 instead of a 5, not because of the crowds, which are to be expected, but because of the constant tour groups going through, one after another, and guides speaking very loudly in some of the smaller galleries. I would recommend that the museum consider having groups only go through at certain hours, so those not in groups can stand back and enjoy.

Let me make it clear, I love Salvador Dali, many don't, but I think he is a genius, hey you have to be to produce some of the rubbish he did.
I was so excited to visit this museum and what a disappointment.
The museum has no control over numbers of visitors. We arrived an 10.15 in the morning and could hardly see anything because of the hundreds of idiots taking photographs of everything in it (buy a postcard, it's better quality). Booked and timed entry, as at the Dali house in Cadaques, would be a much better idea. Keep the numbers under control and everyone will enjoy it more.
As I have said I love Dali but he did, like every artist, produce a lot of dross. There is no editorial control, dross is next to genius.
Maybe because of the crowds but even with a map I managed to miss what I really wanted to see above all else (Mae West).
This could, and should, be a wonderful experience, but it just ain't.

My tips:
-Show up when it opens to skip the line, which can be unbelievably long like a Disneyland line
-Research the ticket options so you're not surprised - the prices aren't bad
-Allow plenty of time to meander and enjoy the museum
-Check out the Joies exhibit which is awesome
-Take a camera for lots of fun pictures inside and outside the building
-Explore the art on the outside of the building and down the little side streets just off the building (there are some really cool, funky statues)

quote: Absolutely Amazing - Get A Guided Tour
reviewnospace: I am writing this after literally just coming back from this museum, it's incredible. Arrive super early if you want to go around on your own, however I would recommend a guided tour as you skip the queue completely, which is often at least an hours wait. I had a wonderful guide who spoke complex perfect English, as well as having a deep knowledge of Dali's life and the history behind the design of the museum. We stopped at around 10 different rooms and pieces and the guide gave some history on the piece as well as a personal interpretation of the pieces meaning, which was absolutely fascinating. The tour lasted around 2 hours and was only 8 euros more than standard entry. After the tour is finished you have the opportunity to look around on your own some more if you wish. With the tour you also get stacks of information and knowledge which is not displayed on any of the walls, it's truly amazing the way it is structured and the way Dali planned each aspect of the museum, if you are staying in Costa Brava or Barcelona make the journey it is completely worth it!

You can buy a book for a a nice sum, of money!! and then after entering the museum you are "blessed" with the privilage of spending more money during the exhibit: there are sevaral exhibits that require electric or mechanic movement in order to be displayed in the right manner, in order to "see" these wonders you must insert coins of 1-2 Euro in the machine as if you were in some arcade or amusement park!!
As a consumer I felt taken advantage of. I was so frustrated about these things that the content of the exhibits did not reallly impress me.

quote: He was one of a kind

quote: Outstanding - the only reason for going to Figueres - but a great one
reviewnospace: I adore this Museum. I've now been twice - and I would go again. It's over the top, highly imaginative, extremely entertaining - and an absolutely must do if you are anywhere near the Costa Brava. I can't even start to recommend it enough. Any one piece of art would be worth the trip - and there are hundreds. Do get at least the guide book (an extra 6.5 euro) - you will miss so much without something to point out Dali's jokes, puns, giggles, and pokes. Go. Please Go.

reviewnospace: A very broad range of Dali's body of work is on display in this somewhat kitschy theatre/museum. The price of admission is relatively high, and many of the displays inside require some Euro coins to operate in order to get the full creative effect. While the natural light of the theatre windows gives the galleries an airy feeling, there is often glare on some of the works, which makes viewing a little awkward. But the range of Dali's talent seemed limitless, from silly and profane to vibrant and contemplative. My appreciation for his work was greatly expanded by this visit.
titleopinion: Eccentric but enjoyable. A very broad range of Dali's body of work is on display in this somewhat kitschy theatre/museum. The price of admission is relatively high, and many of the displays inside require some Euro coins to operate in order to get the full creative effect. While the natural light of the theatre windows gives the galleries an airy feeling, there is often glare on some of the works, which makes viewing a little awkward. But the range of Dali's talent seemed limitless, from silly and profane to vibrant and contemplative. My appreciation for his work was greatly expanded by this visit.

quote: A temple to an extra-ordinary man
reviewnospace: You don't have to like the works of Dali to come here. It is Dali and so much more. And lots of things that Dali created that you never would have imagined. Not just droopy clocks! Like him or not, he was an extraordinary force on the world of art, and changed some of our perspectives. This museum was largely his own work (I believe) and is as large as his own ego. There are also other exhibits always worth seeing - and follow up with a visit to his whitewashed house by the sea at Port LLigat.

quote: Interesting but not value for money
reviewnospace: It cost us 12 each to enter, compare thos to 3 for Cosmocaixa (Barcelona science museum) or the Picasso museum, both of which are a wonderful day out, it seems overpriced, however it is a must see. Neither of us know much about art, we had read a little about Dalí before we arrived but because the art work on display does not have any explanations next to it, and most of them don't even have titles, we were just looking at it and thinking what is this? (Some of it reminded me of Tony Hancock's 'the rebel') Because there were no guided tours or information leaflets it relly felt like a wasted opportunity to learn something. The nature of the building means that it is difficult to look at some works and you have to double back on yourself a lot, which doesn't really matter but it was so full of school trips, bored teenagers who seemed to be unsupervised and were running around not looking at anything but shouting at each other and sitting in front of things which made it a very uncomfortable experience, maybe they should limit the size of groups and take them round with a guide or only allow groups in at certains times because it really spoiled the experience. As we left we both felt disappointed, I'm sure they make plenty of money but why not put in a little extra effort and give people a really amazing experience instead of a mediocre one.

reviewnospace: The Dali Theatre-Museum is a day trip from Barcelona. It's definitely worth a visit and I highly recommend a guided visit. Book ahead of time. Don't miss the jewelry room with the ruby hearth--it moves!
